    "body": "@tejohnso I think you are getting confused between available features and security levels.  The point I was making is that if you have access to the WebView element then by definition you can create a renderer process with `nodeIntegration` enabled.  This would be very bad if a renderer process without `nodeIntegration` could create itself a new renderer process with `nodeIntegration` enabled.\r\n\r\nAs such it is only safe for processes with `nodeIntegration` already enabled to create WebView's.\r\n\r\n> having nodeIntegration improves security when those features are present\r\n\r\nHaving `nodeIntegration` doesn't improve security technically, having more node API's is **less** secure so it is only allowed when the parent renderer process also has `nodeIntegration`.  This grid might explain it a bit better.\r\n\r\n| Parent Renderer `nodeIntegration` | Can use Node API's | Can use WebView | Can use Node API's through WebView |\r\n|------------------------------------|--------------------|---|---|\r\n| Enabled | Yes | Yes | Yes |\r\n| Disabled | No | No | No |\r\n\r\nYou should be able to see that having a row in that table `\"Disabled | No | Yes | Yes\"` would be ridiculously unsafe"
  },
